- VSCode Version: 0.10.11
- OS Version: Mac OS X 10.11.3

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Open a new project and make sure `editor.tabSize` is set to `auto`
2. Create a new file `test.js` with the following contents

``` js
'use strict';

const multiline = `
  this is a multiline
  string with 2 space indentation
`;

function log(str) {
    console.log(str);
}

log(multiline);
```

> Note: The indentation inside the `log` function is a `tab` but GitHub parses it to 4 spaces. So make sure to convert this to a `tab` when copy-pasting.
1. Close the file and reopen it

<img width="310" alt="screen shot 2016-03-28 at 21 33 32" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1913805/14087927/c1070236-f52c-11e5-939f-3201ba14eeb2.png">

As you can see, it sets the `tabSize` to `2` because it is `2` in the multiline template literal. But it shouldn't take strings into account to determine this.

// @alexandrudima

- VSCode Version: 0.10.11
- OS Version: OS X 10.10.5
- Typescript: 1.8.9
- Node: 5.9.0

Possibly related to #2157, #1384

After upgrading typescript from 1.6 to 1.8.9, and node from 0.12 to 5.9.0, I noticed breakpoints no longer working and other strange behavior.
- Debugger fails to stop at breakpoints in .ts file
- Debugger shows .js file instead of .ts when attaching to node --debug-brk
- Double entries for same breakpoint appear in "breakpoints" pane

Its been difficult to produce a good test case for this bug due to nondeterministic behavior. I've seen symptoms appear or disappear after:
- Commenting/uncommenting parts of the code and recompiling
- Copying the .ts file to an identical copy and debugging

Possible causes that have been ruled out:
- "outDir" setting (separate outDir or not makes no difference)
- "typescript.tsdk" 1.8.9 mismatch (tried setting to installed version of typescript vs bundled 1.8.2)
- Code with promises or callbacks (issue was produced in case with only console.log())
- Breakpoint being on first line (breakpoints throughout entire code may fail)

Steps to Reproduce:

test.ts:

``` typescript
import fs = require('fs');
var cb1 = function(err, stats) {
    console.log('break here 1');
};
fs.stat('.', cb1);

var cb2 = function() {
    console.log('break here 2');
}
setTimeout(cb2, 1000);
```

tsconfig.json:

``` json
{
    "compilerOptions": {
        "target": "es6",
        "module": "commonjs",
        "sourceMap": true
    }
}
```

launch.json:

``` json
{
    "version": "0.2.0",
    "configurations": [
        {
            "name": "Attach",
            "request": "attach",
            "type": "node",
            "port": 5858,
            "sourceMaps": true
        }
    ]
}
```
1. tsc
2. node --debug-brk test.js
3. Set breakpoints in ts file and attach to process
4. Commenting/uncommenting the top or bottom section and retrying causes the breakpoint issue to manifest eventually

- VSCode Version: 0.10.11
- OS Version: Max OS 10.11.4

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Create a JSX file with the following contents:

   ``` jsx
   import React from 'react';

   export default ({message}) => {
       return (
           <li>{message}. Something else.</li>
       )
   }
   ```
2. Format the code (shift-alt-f)

Notice that the space between the full-stop and "Something" gets removed.

Expected:
Text content within JSX tags should not be modified.

- VSCode Version: 0.10.11
- OS Version: Windows 8.1

The problem is observed only in the following scenario:

```
for (i=0; attr && i<attr.length; i++) {
    if (attr[i].specified) {
        props[attr[i].name] = attr[i].value;
        hasAttrib = true;
    }
}
```

